    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i keep getting this \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error on my ec2 instances in us-east-1. it only happens intermittently and usually during peak traffic. i checked the security groups and everything looks theoretically fine but the logs are driving me crazy. \n\nhere is a snippet from cloudwatch:\n2023-10-27T14:22:01Z iid: 4922-X | status: 502 | error: connection reset by peer | client_ip: 192.168.1.45\n\nany idea what might be causing this? specifically looking at network config or security groups.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error, especially during peak traffic, often points to an issue on the *other* end of the connection, not just your EC2 instance's configuration. This intermittent nature suggests resource exhaustion or a timeout issue on the client or an intermediary service. While security groups are usually fine for inbound/outbound rules, this error can sometimes indicate an upstream load balancer or firewall actively closing the connection due to inactivity or overload. You might want to check the network metrics (like CPU utilization and network I/O) on your instances during those peak times.",
      "source": "target",
