    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the metrics and cpu/network looks okay on the instances themselves. its weird because it doesnt seem to correlate with a specific spike in load, it just feels totally random. could it be something at the VPC level or maybe a stateful firewall issue? like something cutting the connection without warning?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the instance metrics are fine and the error is random, you should investigate stateful components outside the direct EC2 workload. A VPC firewall, Network ACLs, or even the underlying AWS load balancer health checks could be prematurely terminating connections. Check any NAT gateways or third-party firewalls situated between the client and your EC2 instances, as these are common culprits for abrupt connection resets. Also, examine the specific service running on your EC2 instances for connection pooling or socket exhaustion issues.",
      "source": "target",
